                  <div class="accordion_head">What is the difference between a division and a subsidiary?<span class="plusminus">+</span></div>
                  <div class="accordion_body" style="display: none;">
                     <p>Divisions are part of a larger parent company and therefore do not operate as a separate legal entity, nor do they hire. This means that a division, although it can operate under a different name, is still a piece of the entity itself. An example of a division is LinkedIn Marketing Solutions. LinkedIn Marketing Solutions is a division of LinkedIn.<br>A subsidiary, on the other hand, is an entirely different company. Subsidiaries are separate and distinct legal entities, which are owned by a separate (usually larger) entity. An example of a subsidiary is LinkedIn, which is a subsidiary of Microsoft.</p>
                  </div>
                  <div class="accordion_head">What happens when pages are acquired?<span class="plusminus">+</span></div>
                  <div class="accordion_body" style="display: none;">
                     <p>Checking the Employee roll up box for Affiliate pages will simply aggregate the number of employees on Affiliate pages to the Parent page. Neither the employee association, logo, or text will reflect the Parent company. However, employees for affiliate pages will show up when members search view employees from the Parent page.</p>
                     <p>Please see HC article <a target="_blank" href="https://www.linkedin.com/help/lms/answer/a565259">here</a></p>
                  </div>
